Certainly! Below is a simple HTML file that creates a 256x256 pixel canvas using embedded CSS and JavaScript. This web app will display a grid of squares, each representing a pixel. You can modify the colors of the squares by clicking on them.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>256x256 Pixel Grid</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
        #pixelCanvas {
            display: grid;
            grid-template-columns: repeat(256, 20px);
            grid-template-rows: repeat(256, 20px);
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }
        .pixel {
            width: 20px;
            height: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            box-sizing: border-box;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="pixelCanvas"></div>

    <script>
        const pixelCanvas = document.getElementById('pixelCanvas');

        // Create a 256x256 grid of pixels
        for (let i = 0; i < 256 * 256; i++) {
            const pixel = document.createElement('div');
            pixel.classList.add('pixel');
            pixel.addEventListener('click', () => {
                pixel.style.backgroundColor = getRandomColor();
            });
            pixelCanvas.appendChild(pixel);
        }

        // Function to generate a random color
        function getRandomColor() {
            const letters = '0123456789ABCDEF';
            let color = '#';
            for (let i = 0; i < 6; i++) {
                color += letters[Math.floor(Math.random() * 16)];
            }
            return color;
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions to Use:
1. Copy the above code into a text editor.
2. Save the file with a `.html` extension, for example, `pixelGrid.html`.
3. Open the saved file in a web browser.

You will see a 256x256 grid of squares. Clicking on any square will change its color to a random color. Enjoy experimenting with the pixel grid!
